      ],
      "period": {
        "listed_date": "2020-04-20",
        "effective_date": "2020-04-20",
        "is_indefinite": true,
        "last_updated": [
          "\n        ",
          "\n        ",
          "\n      "
        ]
      },
      "status": "active",
      "reference_number": "CFi.013",
      "remarks": "Martin Koumtamadji founded the FDPC in 2005. He joined the Séléka\ncoalition in December 2012 before leaving it in April 2013 after the rebels took power in Bangui.\nAfter being arrested in Cameroon, he was then transferred to Brazzaville in the Republic of\nCongo. He always remained in command of his troops on the ground in the CAR even when he\nwas in Brazzaville before returning to the CAR (between November 2014 and 2019). The FDPC\nsigned the Political Agreement for Peace and Reconciliation in the CAR on 6 February 2019 but\nMartin Koumtamadji remains a threat to the peace, stability and security of the CAR. Photo available\nfor inclusion in the INTERPOL-UN Security Council Special Notice.",
      "raw_source_data": {
        "source_format": "xml",
        "source_specific_fields": {
          "un:dataId": "6908840",
          "un:versionNum": "1",
          "un:entityType": "individual"
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "https://www.ammitto.org/entry/un/CFi.014",
      "entity_id": "https://www.ammitto.org/entity/un/CFi.014",
      "authority": {
        "id": "un",
        "name": "United Nations",
        "country_code": "UN"
      },
      "regime": {
        "name": "Central African Republic",
        "code": "CAR"
      },
      "effects": [
        {
          "effect_type": "asset_freeze",
          "scope": "full"
        },
        {
          "effect_type": "travel_ban",
          "scope": "full"
        }
      ],
      "period": {
        "listed_date": "2020-08-05",
        "effective_date": "2020-08-05",
        "is_indefinite": true,
        "last_updated": [
          "\n        ",
          "\n      "
        ]
      },
      "status": "active",
      "reference_number": "CFi.014",
      "remarks": "Bi Sidi Souleman leads the Central African Republic (CAR)-based militia group Return, Reclamation, Rehabilitation (3R) which has killed, tortured, raped, and displaced civilians and engaged in arms trafficking, illegal taxation activities, and warfare with other militias since its creation in 2015. Bi Sidi Souleman himself has also participated in torture. On 6 February 2019, 3R signed the Political Agreement for Peace and Reconciliation in the CAR but has engaged in acts violating the Agreement and remains a threat to the peace, stability and security of the CAR. For instance, on 21 May 2019, 3R killed 34 unarmed civilians in three villages, summarily executing adult males. Bi Sidi Souleman openly confirmed to a UN Entity that he had ordered 3R elements to the villages on the date of the attacks, but did not admit to giving the orders for 3R to kill.  In December 2020, after having joined a coalition of armed groups established to disrupt the electoral process, Bi Sidi Souleman was reportedly killed during fighting.  INTERPOL-UN Security Council Special Notice web link:https://www.interpol.int/en/How-we-work/Notices/View-UN-Notices-Individuals",
      "raw_source_data": {
        "source_format": "xml",
        "source_specific_fields": {
          "un:dataId": "6908845",
          "un:versionNum": "1",
          "un:entityType": "individual"
        }
      }
    },
